{
  "source_translation": "Thousands of people gathered at La Casa Rosada to bid farewell to their idol. Three individuals hired by the funeral home responsible for preparing the Argentine star's body for viewing took several photographs next to the coffin. In two images, the three men can be seen posing beside the open casket, two of them giving a thumbs up, apparently in a sign of approval. The photographs ended up being shared on social media while Maradona was being mourned at La Casa Rosada, the presidential palace, provoking anger and outrage among many Argentines. 'Widespread rejection,' noted the country's major newspapers. Matías Morla, the agent and lawyer of the football legend, called one of the individuals who took the photo a 'scoundrel' and warned that he would take action over the incident. 'For the memory of my friend, I will not rest until he pays for such an aberration,' he said on Twitter, where criticism against those involved has accumulated, but some comments also justify their actions due to the fanaticism surrounding 'the Ten.' One of the individuals involved, however, has already publicly apologized and stated that he has received death threats over the situation. 'I apologize.' According to Claudio Fernández, the idea of taking a photo next to the open casket, accompanied by his son, was 'something...",
  "candidate_translation": "This year we have heard about gravitational waves, been alarmed by the Zika virus, and learned about the rocky exoplanet Proxima b."
}

{
  "source_translation": "Rondón became the first Venezuelan to score a hat-trick in England. The star of the Vinotinto received praise from the sports press in the UK on Thursday after scoring three goals in 13 minutes, making him the first player from his country to achieve the prestigious hat-trick in English football. To top it off, he scored all three with his head, becoming only the second player in Premier League history to accomplish this feat. The other was Duncan Ferguson in 1997. With his three headed goals, Rondón now has seven for the season. Analysts highlight that in addition to his finishing ability, he works hard on the field, a crucial task for a team that usually fights to avoid relegation each year but has transformed into a major revelation this season. 'Three perfect headers. The power, the precision, was simply fantastic tonight.' WBA is in seventh place in the table behind Manchester United, although they have scored more goals than the team managed by Portuguese José Mourinho. 'Three perfect headers. The power, the precision, was simply fantastic tonight,' acknowledged English football legend Alan Shearer, whose comments often resonate with fans. Since arriving at the central England team from Zenit in San...",
  "candidate_translation": "Salomón Rondón is experiencing his best moment in English football."
}

{
  "source_translation": "A can of tomato soup contains no less than 6 teaspoons of salt. And if you think that counting the teaspoons you add to your morning coffee plus some sweet treat during the day is enough, as we show in this video, you are mistaken. How much added sugar is hidden in savory food? Processed savory food also contains added sugar, and sometimes a single dish can exceed the recommended amount for the entire day. One of the challenges in controlling sugar consumption is detecting it on food nutrition labels, as it can appear under different names. For example, the new nutrition information labels approved by the U.S. Food and Drug Administration. According to the National Health Service of the United Kingdom, there are more than a dozen names that refer to sugar, such as fructose, glucose, sucrose, and molasses. To prevent consumers from having to take advanced chemistry courses to understand food nutrition information, the U.S. Food and Drug Administration announced in May that the label format will be modified in the country. Starting in July 2018, added sugar will be shown separately and expressed in grams and as a percentage based on a 2,000-calorie diet. These are the...",
  "candidate_translation": "The World Health Organization (WHO) recommends that added sugar consumption should not exceed 10% of daily caloric intake."
}

{
  "source_translation": "The police were guarding a protest for the death of two Black citizens. No police officers had died in a single event since the attack on the Twin Towers in New York on 9/11. That day, 71 lost their lives: 37 from the Port Authority of New York and New Jersey and 23 from the New York Police Department. The Dallas incident was not a random event. The main suspect, Micah Xavier Johnson, made threats against officers before being shot and, according to the Dallas police, stated that he wanted to kill white police officers. In terms of victim count, the second deadliest incident occurred nearly a century ago, in 1917, when nine officials died due to a bomb placed in a police station in Milwaukee. It is believed to have been an action by an anarchist group, although the perpetrators were never caught. 71 law enforcement officers died during the attacks on September 11, 2001. In the last century, there have been three other incidents where eight officials died. The most recent was the bombing in 1995 by Timothy McVeigh and Terry Nichols against a federal building in Oklahoma City, which killed 168 people, including four Secret Service agents. The other two cases occurred in 1950, when eight officials died...",
  "candidate_translation": "The death of five police officers in Dallas (Texas) this Thursday in an attack carried out by snipers is the deadliest event for police in the United States since the September 11, 2001 attacks."
}

{
  "source_translation": "Despite centuries of domestication, European strawberries remained a small delicacy in 1711. However, in a region between the Andes and the Pacific, indigenous people had been cultivating and enhancing them for nearly a thousand years. Julius de Berry from Antwerp had gifted a bowl full of ripe wild strawberries; as a reward, the king named the family 'Fraise' (strawberry in French). 800 years later, another king of France, Louis XIV, was worried because his country was not faring well in the War of Spanish Succession and feared that a peace treaty would leave the court of Versailles without access to the riches of America. In 1711, he decided to send a spy to the south of the New World to gather information. The chosen one turned out to be none other than Amedée François Frézier. The surname had changed slightly, as the family had settled in Scotland in the Middle Ages, as part of the entourage of the French ambassador, and there it became Frazer; upon returning to France, it became Frézier, but Amedée was a descendant of Julius, who had gifted strawberries to Charles 'the Simple'. In one of those curious coincidences of history, his journey to South America would forever change that delicacy that so pleased the monarch.",
  "candidate_translation": "When in 1364 King Charles V of France received a gift from his cousin, King Charles IV of Luxembourg, he was delighted."
}

{
  "source_translation": "Statistics show a reduction in attacks. But the threat continues. Potts told the BBC that several factors led to Somali pirates being 'contained and restrained' and that a joint naval forces operation at one of their land bases last May had a profound effect and is deterring pirates from going to sea. However, the rear admiral also warned that progress against piracy is weak and still reversible. Statistics reveal a dramatic reduction in piracy attacks off the Somali coast. In 2011, according to EU Navfor Somalia, there were 151 verified attacks on sizable ships, and 25 vessels were successfully pirated. So far this year, the number of attacks has dropped to 31, and only five ships have been captured, the last one in May. 'October and November would normally be two of the most active months for maritime piracy as they fall between the two monsoon seasons,' says Potts. 'But this year they have been surprisingly quiet.' The source of the problem is not at sea, but on land. Potts lists four factors for the reduction in piracy. First is the use of private security guards on ships...",
  "candidate_translation": "British Rear Admiral Philip Potts, commander of the European Union naval force in Somalia, says piracy in the waters off the Horn of Africa is at its lowest point in five years."
}

{
  "source_translation": "Guillermo Del Toro dedicated his award to young Latin American directors. The Mexican director said that the coveted award was a confirmation that one should hold on to the things they believe in. \"In my case, monsters,\" he noted. Del Toro's latest film tells the story of a cleaning lady (Sally Hawkins) who falls in love with an aquatic creature. The film \"Foxtrot,\" by Israeli director Samuel Maoz, won the Silver Lion of the Grand Jury. French director Xavier Legrand won the Silver Lion for Best Director for his drama Jusqu'à la Garde (Custody). Del Toro dedicated his award to young Latin American directors. \"As a Mexican, I dedicate this award to all Mexicans and Latin American directors who dream of doing something like a parable, to those who are told it cannot be done. Yes, it can be done,\" he said.",
  "candidate_translation": "Mexican Guillermo Del Toro won this award for young Latin American directors."
}

{
  "source_translation": "Peña Nieto: \"Mexico will not pay for any wall\" With these words, in a recorded video message, the President of Mexico, Enrique Peña Nieto, responded to the executive order issued this Wednesday by U.S. President Donald Trump to expand a wall on the border between the two countries. \"Mexico does not believe in walls. I have said it time and again: Mexico will not pay for any wall,\" Peña Nieto assured. The Mexican president did not clarify whether he would cancel the meeting with Trump in Washington, scheduled for January 31 at the White House. Legislators and political party leaders have requested this since Tuesday night when Trump announced the construction of the wall on his Twitter account. Peña Nieto stated that he would decide \"the next steps\" after consulting with the Senate, state governors, and the final report from Foreign Secretary Luis Videgaray and Economy Secretary Ildefonso Guajardo. The officials met at the White House with part of the U.S. president's team this Wednesday. The meeting lasted about 8 hours. However, in an interview with Televisa, Videgaray said that the meeting between Trump and Peña Nieto is still on. \"The working meeting between the presidents next Tuesday is still confirmed. The meeting is still on, confirmed,\" he insisted. However, to increase pressure, this Thursday the president...",
  "candidate_translation": "\"We demand respect.\""
}

{
  "source_translation": "The new bridge features the latest technology. The new bridge is called San Giorgio, made of steel and concrete, and was designed by the renowned Genoese architect Renzo Piano. The new structure boasts high technology. It has a dehumidification system and four maintenance robots responsible for detecting any type of erosion. The works were completed a year after the demolition of the remains of the previous bridge. \"On one hand, I feel proud, but at the same time, this bridge is born from a tragedy. This will never be forgotten,\" said the 82-year-old architect to the BBC. Tragedy On August 14, 2018, after a heavy storm and intense rains, the Morandi bridge collapsed, and 210 meters of its structure and one of the support towers fell. Vehicles that were then crossing the bridge fell in a cascade, and several apartment blocks around were crushed. 210 meters of the Morandi bridge came down, causing vehicles to fall and buildings to be crushed. 43 people died. At the inauguration ceremony of the new bridge, the name of each victim will be read aloud as a form of tribute. However, some relatives of the deceased prefer not to attend. \"We will not be at the inauguration; we do not want the tragedy to turn into a carnival,\" said Egle Possett, whose sister...",
  "candidate_translation": "The new bridge in Genoa, which replaces the one that collapsed two years ago, was inaugurated this Wednesday."
}

{
  "source_translation": "Kandovan, in Iran, is one of the most fascinating destinations shaped by nature: it looks like a giant termite colony of mud cones. But sometimes the most fascinating cities and towns are those shaped by nature, often with surprisingly surreal results. To find the most spectacular natural places where people actually live, we turned to the Q&A site Quora. Its users told us about caves carved into volcanic rock and cities built in meteorite craters, among other destinations that look nothing like the standard tourist brochure. Kandovan, Iran Since the 13th century, or even earlier, the residents of this village have carved their conical houses into the soft volcanic rock of the area, a legacy of the previous eruptions of the now inactive Mount Sahand volcano. Located 55km south of Tabriz, the village looks like a giant colony of mud cones filled with holes. In addition to having a surreal appearance, the troglodyte homes provide natural heating and cooling, says Quora user Kaushik Parashar from Guwahati, India. 'The hardened material provides efficient insulation for the summers and harsh winters,' he says. Travelers can also enjoy the benefits of these dwellings...",
  "candidate_translation": "When planning our vacations, we often focus on the most well-known cities and towns."
}

{
  "source_translation": "Each of its projectiles costs more than $800,000. In fact, it is the most expensive warship ever built by the U.S. Navy: it cost over $4 billion. Its naval engineering system is so advanced that it can hit targets more than 128 kilometers away. It is designed to be registered by radars as a simple fishing boat, thanks to its angular shape. \"It is simply gigantic once it starts to approach,\" noted Lawrence Pye, a lobster fisherman whose radar detected a fishing boat of only 12 to 15 meters in length. However, the 14,500-ton vessel measures no less than 185 meters long. It is the jewel of the U.S. Navy, but the price of its ammunition is as exorbitant as its size. Its development began in the 1990s and it is the first of a \"new generation of warships that must adapt to the current global political landscape,\" stated its manufacturer, Bath Iron Works, on its website. But it has a small (or rather, big) drawback: each of its projectiles costs more than $800,000. And now the Pentagon is considering that perhaps this weapon, as advanced as it is, is too costly. Exorbitant price. This October, during a presentation ceremony in Baltimore, U.S., Admiral Harry Harris, head of the Command...",
  "candidate_translation": "The most expensive warship ever built by the U.S. Navy, the USS Zumwalt, has a small (or rather, big) drawback: each of its projectiles costs more than $800,000."
}

{
  "source_translation": "At a press conference, Putin stated that the ousting of Ukrainian President Viktor Yanukovych was an 'unconstitutional coup and an armed takeover of power.' He also denied that Russian soldiers had besieged Ukrainians in the Crimean Peninsula, claiming that all forces there were 'pro-Russia self-defense forces.' Crimea has become the focal point of the crisis in Ukraine after a series of violent protests forced Yanukovych from power. Troops in apparently Russian uniforms surround Ukrainian military bases. Russia effectively controls the peninsula. Thus, the question that resonates is: does Russia have sufficient and legitimate reasons to intervene in Crimea? In BBC Mundo, we analyze Russia's justifications for a possible intervention in eastern Ukraine. Read: The (dis)balance of military power between Russia and Ukraine. What drives Russia to defend Crimea? Soviet leader Nikita Khrushchev handed Crimea to Ukraine in 1954. Historical connections to the peninsula date back to the times of Catherine the Great in the 18th century when Russia conquered southeastern Ukraine and the Crimean Peninsula from the Ottoman Empire. In 1954, Crimea was given to Ukraine as a gift from Soviet leader Nikita Khrushchev, who was half Ukrainian. Just ten years earlier, Joseph Stalin had...",
  "candidate_translation": "Russian President Vladimir Putin defended on Tuesday the decision to send troops to Ukraine, stating that his goal is to protect Russian citizens living there."
}

{
  "source_translation": "In recent months, state media have publicly celebrated several achievements in advanced technology. Or at least that's what they say. As with most things in that country, it's hard to verify what's true and what's not. Nevertheless, it is significant that they are giving importance to technology. Recently, state media have publicly celebrated various achievements in advanced technology, including a 'smart home system.' Beyond the purpose of propaganda, the emphasis on this sector reflects North Korea's intention to leverage technology to improve its economy, a key goal for Supreme Leader Kim Jong-un. One of the most recent ventures is a new wifi service called Mirae, which allows mobile services to access the state-approved intranet network in the capital, Pyongyang. State television showed in early November how an Airang 171 smartphone was used to access Mirae during the 'Exhibition of Technological Achievements.' The U.S.-based monitoring page 38North noted that this was the first time an outdoor wifi service was mentioned in North Korean media and it operates alongside two cellular networks that provide data connection services...",
  "candidate_translation": "The North Korean government announced this Monday that North Korea will undergo an industrial revolution."
}

{
  "source_translation": "Toyota has benefited from sales in the markets of Japan and the United States. The automotive giant predicts a net profit of $9.7 billion for the financial year ending March 31, 2013, thanks to a strong recovery in sales in Japan and the U.S. Toyota based its profit projection after recording a 221% increase in the quarter from July to September compared to the same period last year. \"During the first six months of this fiscal year, we have seen a significant increase in production across all regions compared to the same period last year, when we suffered a shortage of parts supply,\" said Satoshi Ozawa, executive vice president of Toyota. However, the Japanese firm showed caution as its sales could be affected by the ongoing territorial dispute between Japan and China and the severe crisis affecting several countries in Europe.",
  "candidate_translation": "Toyota expects an increase in its profits due to a rise in sales in Japan and the United States."
}

{
  "source_translation": "In Brazil, it is practically a given that the Senate will suspend Rousseff for up to 180 days. The news comes just as it is considered almost certain that the Senate will suspend Rousseff next week to subject her to an impeachment trial. The request to open a judicial investigation against the president was sent by the attorney general to the Supreme Court confidentially and, according to reports, includes a request to investigate former president Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva. For the procedure to be opened, it requires the authorization of Teori Zavascki, the Supreme Court minister (judge) overseeing the processes related to the massive corruption scheme at Petrobras. The suspicions The prosecutor's request is based on suspicions that Rousseff attempted to appoint Lula as a minister in her government to give him special judicial status that would prevent his potential arrest due to the Petrobras scandal, the media reports. Judge Sérgio Moro disclosed in March a recording of a phone conversation where Rousseff informed Lula that she would send him the act of his appointment to use 'in case of necessity.' The president has denied that those words were related to the Petrobras case and stated that she sent the document because she did not know if Lula could attend the act of his appointment. Both Rousseff...",
  "candidate_translation": "Brazilian judge Sérgio Moro announced on Tuesday that President Dilma Rousseff will be suspended for the first time."
}

