{
  "source_translation": "Kim Jong-un next to a computer resembling an Apple. The Red Star operating system was designed to superficially resemble Apple's OS X, but it has hidden features that allow it to tag files and link them to specific individuals. The hidden tools were discovered by Florian Grunow and Niklaus Schiess, two German researchers who conducted the analysis last month. Grunow and Schiess presented their findings on Sunday at the 'Chaos Communication Congress,' a conference held in Hamburg with experts in security, cryptography, privacy, and freedom of expression. The researchers thoroughly reviewed the code of the Red Star 3.0 operating system, which appeared online a year ago. As Grunow explained to the BBC, the system's developers 'did a very good job' copying the basic design and functionality of Apple computers. North Korea's previous operating system resembled Windows more. But they added a special feature: any file uploaded to the system with a USB drive or other storage device can be tagged, allowing the State to track its path from one machine to another. Red Star can also identify unwanted files and delete them without authorization. A very sophisticated system...",
  "candidate_translation": "North Korea's spy operating system, according to reports on Sunday, is designed to create a North Korean spy operating system."
}

