  "source_translation": "The police were guarding a protest for the death of two Black citizens. No police officers had died in a single event since the attack on the Twin Towers in New York on 9/11. That day, 71 lives were lost: 37 from the Port Authority of New York and New Jersey and 23 from the New York Police Department. The Dallas incident was not a random event. The main suspect, Micah Xavier Johnson, made threats against officers before being shot and, according to the Dallas police, stated that he wanted to kill white police officers. In terms of victim count, the second deadliest incident occurred nearly a century ago, in 1917, when nine officials died due to a bomb placed in a police station in Milwaukee. It is believed to have been an action by an anarchist group, although the perpetrators were never caught. 71 law enforcement officers died during the attacks on September 11, 2001. In the last century, there have been three other incidents where eight officials died. The most recent was the bombing in 1995 by Timothy McVeigh and Terry Nichols against a federal building in Oklahoma City, which killed 168 people, including four Secret Service agents. The other two cases occurred in 1950, when eight officials died...",
