{
  "source_translation": "Russia has been an indispensable ally for Bashar al-Assad's government in Syria. Currently, he is a professor and a member of the Institute for Public Diplomacy and Communication at George Washington University. The following article for the BBC reflects his personal opinion on Moscow's growing influence in seeking a solution to the Syrian crisis. Read: Why is Russia becoming more involved in the war in Syria? ----------------------------------- End of Perhaps you might also be interested It is difficult to get an accurate idea from the dramatic images of refugees and immigrants heading towards Europe that we have seen in recent weeks. Many of them in boats, others by train, and others on foot. Who are they? Why are they fleeing in seemingly increasing numbers? Why now? What has changed? After five years of civil war, the question is whether Syria will continue to exist as a single state. Europe is trying to provide a coherent response to the problem, taking into account the variety of capacities and political trends of its 28 members. From the compassionate pragmatism of German Chancellor Angela Merkel to the angry populism of Hungarian Prime Minister Viktor Orban. And these refugees and immigrants are fleeing from many conflicts and crises. But the main common factor seems to be the civil war in Syria,...",
  "candidate_translation": "American journalist Jonathan Marcus was one of the first journalists to arrive in Russia in 2011."
}

{
  "source_translation": "For experts, Ingvar Kamprad transformed the way home furniture is marketed (Photo courtesy: Ikea). Kamprad died \"peacefully\" at his home in Smaland, the statement noted. The company said that Kamprad was \"one of the greatest entrepreneurs of the 20th century.\" Throughout his career, the founder of Ikea faced scrutiny over his past ties to the Nazis, which he called \"the biggest mistake\" of his life. He attributed his involvement to \"youthful stupidity.\" \"He worked until the end of his life, remaining true to his own motto: most homes are yet to be made,\" the company added. In 2013, Kamprad decided to step down from Ikea's board. The teenage investment The billionaire was born in 1926 in Smaland and founded Ikea when he was 17. He had used money his father gave him as a gift for his good grades in school, despite being dyslexic. Ingvar Kamprad founded IKEA in 1943. Here he is at a tribute with Princess Victoria of Sweden. \"Ingvar Kamprad was a great entrepreneur typical of southern Sweden: very hardworking and stubborn, with much warmth and a playful sparkle in his eyes,\" the company wrote when announcing his passing. The designs created by his company became very popular partly due to their simplicity and low cost. Furniture design expert Jeff Banks indicated that the...",
  "candidate_translation": "The founder of Ikea, Ingvar Kamprad, became an icon of the modern economy."
}

{
  "source_translation": "The image of Abdul trying to sell pens moved many internet users. The man is Abdul Halim Attar, a Palestinian refugee from Yarmouk in Syria, and his daughter's name is Reem. We know this thanks to an Icelandic activist, Gissur Simonarson, who managed to locate both of them. Simonarson, who runs the news site Conflict News, posted the photo on his Twitter account after seeing it shared, and it quickly gained traction among his 6,000 followers. He then decided to search for the man and, in less than half an hour, with the help of local journalists and activists in Lebanon, he managed to track him down. Successful campaign Then, on Thursday, Simonarson opened a Twitter account and started a crowdfunding campaign through Indiegogo, aiming to raise $5,000 in 15 days for Abdul and his daughter. Less than half an hour after asking for help to find them, Simonarson located Abdul and his daughter Reem. The goal was reached in just 30 minutes. In 22 hours, it had surpassed $60,752 and the amount continues to rise. \"My goal was to get him some help. I didn't expect the great support we are receiving now,\" Simonarson told the BBC. \"Now it seems he could start a new life with this money.\" When Attar learned what had happened, he broke down in tears.",
  "candidate_translation": "The image of a man and a girl at a pen stand in the Lebanese city of Qasar moved many internet users."
}

{
  "source_translation": "The change in timbre was identified in mothers speaking ten different languages, including Spanish, English, Mandarin Chinese, and Hebrew. However, what scientists did not know until now is that they also unconsciously change the timbre. This characteristic is like the fingerprint of our voices. Timbre is what differentiates a piano from a guitar when they play the same note. It makes our voices sound more or less velvety, hoarse, rough, or nasal, and to some extent, it is determined by the physical characteristics of our larynx and vocal cords. Researchers at the Child Laboratory at Princeton University in the United States discovered that mothers unconsciously use a different timbre when speaking to adults compared to when they speak to their babies. This vocal change was identified in mothers speaking nine different languages besides English, including Spanish, Mandarin, and Hebrew. 'There is a consistent pattern among all mothers. They all use the same type of change to switch from one mode to another,' Dr. Elize Piazza, co-author of the study, told the BBC. 'Vocal fingerprints.' The researchers analyzed the speech patterns of 24 women, 12 native English speakers and 12 from other languages. The study's results may be useful in developing...",
  "candidate_translation": "Scientists knew that mothers change the tone and rhythm of their voice when speaking to their babies."
}

{
  "source_translation": "Soros: \"We have to experiment and Uruguay is one of the countries experimenting.\" The name of the 83-year-old Hungarian-American resonated in the debate over cannabis in Uruguay, after it was revealed that Open Society funded a campaign in favor of the law that last week made that country the first to legalize the drug's trade. Soros, a controversial investor, speculator, and philanthropist who in 1992 contributed to triggering a devaluation of the pound sterling, also met in September with Uruguayan President José Mujica to discuss his initiative regarding marijuana. \"As he has influence in some important NGOs, he has been collaborating and will continue to collaborate on that,\" Mujica stated at the end of that meeting in New York. Founded and chaired by Soros, Open Society also funds groups that promote changes in cannabis strategy in the region and the United States, including the Global Commission on Drug Policy, which includes former presidents Fernando Henrique Cardoso (Brazil), Ernesto Zedillo (Mexico), and César Gaviria (Colombia), among other figures. \"Open Society has been a key player in supporting civil society groups that seek to promote an opening\" in drug policy, John Walsh told BBC Mundo.",
  "candidate_translation": "In Uruguay, the United Nations anti-narcotics agency accused him of \"interference.\" And in the United States, the conservative newspaper Washington Times links him to an alleged plan to \"monopolize\" the marijuana market."
}

{
  "source_translation": "Francisco Rodríguez contradicts other Venezuelan economists who oppose the electoral battle. Rodríguez, economic advisor to candidate Henri Falcón, has entered the campaign for the presidential elections in Venezuela on May 20, which is heating up despite much of the opposition calling for non-participation. Maduro, who seeks re-election despite the severe economic crisis of a country in hyperinflation, already has Falcón in his sights, who appears to be his main and almost only rival. Falcón, who was a Chavista, leads the voting intention in several polls and is trying to gather support and break with the abstentionism proposed by a significant part of the opposition, which does not believe the electoral process is clean or fair. Henri Falcón is ahead in the polls two months before the elections. Among the support he already has is that of Rodríguez, 48, who has left his position as chief economist at the Wall Street firm Torino Capital to advise the candidate on economic matters, the root of Venezuela's problems. With Rodríguez's entry into the scene, Maduro stirs up fears of the arrival of neoliberalism represented in the 1970s by economists known as the 'Chicago boys.' The socialist president claims that Rodríguez intends to privatize companies, 'end the economy...",
  "candidate_translation": "Nicolás Maduro has a new enemy: Francisco Rodríguez."
}

