}

{
  "source_translation": "Guardiola has achieved enormous success with Bayern Munich and Barcelona. The former Barcelona coach has been advising the Japanese rugby team. The team's head coach, Eddie Jones, says he approached Guardiola for some advice ahead of the 2015 Rugby World Cup, where Japan will seek its first victory since 1991. 'He is the best football coach in the world, and one always learns from the best,' said the Australian Jones. He explained to the Japanese news agency Kyodo News, 'Rugby and football are very similar in that you always want to move the ball into open spaces, and Bayern Munich and his previous team, Barcelona, have played with the most fantastic passing style you've seen. The principles are exactly the same.'",
  "candidate_translation": "The 'Super Bayern' of Japan, former football coach José Guardiola, advised the Japanese rugby team."
}

{
  "source_translation": "Despite the firmness of the sentence he faces, former president Luis Inácio Lula da Silva remains free. However, in the case of Brazilian Luis Inácio Lula da Silva, that is still to be seen. The judicial ruling this Wednesday against Lula undoubtedly represents a severe setback for the 71-year-old man who presided over Brazil from 2003 to 2010 with enormous popularity and influence in the region. Federal judge Sérgio Moro determined that Lula received approximately $1.1 million in bribes from the construction company OAS, in the form of a remodeled triplex apartment on the coast of São Paulo. Furthermore, Moro—who leads the colossal corruption case involving the state oil company Petrobras—concluded that the leader and pre-candidate of the Workers' Party (PT) for the 2018 elections is barred from holding public office. So, has the political career of Lula come to an end? The federal judge Sérgio Moro determined that Lula received approximately $1.1 million in bribes from the construction company OAS, in the form of a remodeled triplex apartment on the coast of São Paulo. Not necessarily, different Brazilian analysts assert, observing the legal and political situation of the former president. 'We cannot yet say that it is the end of his political career,' warns Cristiano Noronha from the Arco Advice consultancy in Brasília, in dialogue with BBC Mundo. Condemned but...",
  "candidate_translation": "The fact that a former president of Brazil is sentenced to 9 and a half years in prison for corruption is a common occurrence in most countries around the world."
}

{
  "source_translation": "For every 10,000 people (who participated in the study) who consumed 21 grams per day of red and processed meat, 40 were diagnosed with colon cancer. This is the conclusion of a new study from the University of Oxford, funded by the NGO Cancer Research in the UK, which adds evidence about the harm caused by consuming red meat. But how great is the risk? How much is exactly too much red meat? And what makes it harmful? Risk After analyzing information from nearly half a million people over six years, researchers found that 2,609 people developed colorectal cancer. They estimate that consuming 3 slices of bacon per day instead of one can increase the risk of colorectal cancer by 20%. For every 10,000 people (who participated in the study) who consumed 21 grams per day of red and processed meat, 40 were diagnosed with colon cancer. The comparable figure for those who consumed 76 grams per day was 48. It is estimated that one of the proteins in red meat (the one that gives it its red color) can damage the intestine when processed. According to the National Health Service (NHS), 76 grams of cooked red meat is equivalent to a sirloin (the cut of meat from the lower back) of just over 250 grams.",
  "candidate_translation": "Red meat is one of the major sources of colon cancer risk."
}

{
  "source_translation": "It is believed that Snowden is still in the transit area of an airport in Moscow. Six of the countries he has applied to are Latin American: Bolivia, Brazil, Cuba, Ecuador, Nicaragua, and Venezuela. However, the president of the latter country assured the BBC on Tuesday that he has not received any request. \"No one has asked us for it yet,\" he said. President of Ecuador, Rafael Correa, stated in an interview with the British newspaper The Guardian that his country is not considering granting political asylum to Snowden and will only do so if the fugitive steps on Ecuadorian territory. According to WikiLeaks, the other countries to which Snowden applied for asylum include Spain, Austria, China, Finland, France, Germany, Iceland, India, Italy, Ireland, the Netherlands, Norway (whose authorities confirmed receipt), Poland, and Switzerland. He had also applied to Russia, but the authorities of that country reported that Snowden later withdrew the request after a series of conditions imposed by Moscow, mainly that he stop leaking U.S. secret information. It is believed that Snowden is in the transit area of an airport in the capital of Russia.",
  "candidate_translation": "Fugitive Edward Snowden has requested political asylum from 21 countries, according to the newspaper WikiLeaks."
}

{
  "source_translation": "Premier League leader Chelsea faces the Turkish champion tonight in the first leg of their last 16 clash. Former Manchester City coach Mancini noted that Chelsea, who have won the Champions League and Europa League in the last two seasons, are the favorites to advance. Mancini said, \"They have great players who are used to matches like this.\" He believes there is an 80% chance they will progress. Despite Jose Mourinho's claim that his team is too young to win major tournaments, Mancini is convinced Chelsea has the ability to win a trophy this season. The Mancini-Mourinho rivalry flared up earlier this week when Mancini claimed he contributed to Inter's Champions League victory. Mourinho took over Inter after Mancini and won the Champions League with the Italian team. Currently the manager of Chelsea, Mourinho rejected the notion that Mancini had a role in that success, stating, \"Six of my eleven players were not in his squad. So his team would only play with five players in the tournament because I had only five players from his team.\" Mancini emphasizes that former Chelsea forward Didier Drogba and Dutch midfielder Wesley Sneijder are crucial for Galatasaray's hopes of reaching the last eight for the second consecutive season. Tonight's match will not be Drogba's first against his former boss Mourinho.",
  "candidate_translation": "After Chelsea's victory in the Europa League, they are expected to win the Champions League."
}

{
  "source_translation": "A surprise awaits me in the elevator I take to go outside. I see a small piece of paper carefully attached next to the mirror in the elevator. At first, I think it's a lost notice or a for sale/rent sign. But upon closer inspection, I realize that the lines on this paper, prepared with a computer printout, form a poem. It's a poem about leaving one's home, with verses describing the journey in the elevator. By the time I reach the ground floor, the poem has ended. I catch a glimpse of myself in the elevator mirror, smiling under the influence of the poem, which also has a humorous side. I think, 'How strange.' Who put this poem here and why? Who wanted to send what message to whom? I turn the corner and head towards the park right in front of our house. A cool, yet sweet breeze is blowing. Although the trees have not yet blossomed, I can smell the fresh earth and spring as I walk along the winding path with yellow stones in the park. The trees on both sides signal that nature is waking up. When I reach the junction with a fountain where birds come to cool off in the summer, my eyes catch a piece of paper pinned to the trunk of a sycamore tree next to a colorful gazebo. Yes, this is also a poem. And this time, the lines are familiar, written in a pearl-like handwriting. It's a poem by the famous Hungarian poet Endre Ady about nature. As I read the poem,...",
  "candidate_translation": "I wake up early in the morning. The sky is still dark."
}

{
  "source_translation": "In expensive perfumes, Beirut residents sit on verandas sipping their cocktails until dawn, dressed in designer clothes. The city's liberal nature truly does not resemble the region's extremely conservative structure in any way. However, there is another aspect that highlights Beirut's uniqueness: its secret yet vibrant gay life. There are special bars and clubs for homosexuals in the country. These cautious venues do not welcome the media if there are undercover agents inside. 'Obscene images.' However, recent events seem to tarnish Lebanon's reputation, which has been relatively understanding towards gays, lesbians, and transgender individuals. Last year, a cinema in Beirut was raided by police, and over 30 people believed to be gay were detained. To determine whether they had engaged in 'natural' sexual relations, those detained were subjected to anal examinations at the police station. In June, psychiatrist Dr. Nabil Huri stated on one of the country's most-watched television channels that homosexuality is a disease that needs to be treated. Four months later, the screening of a French film depicting a love story between a gay couple was censored at the Beirut Film Festival. The Ministry of Interior deemed the film obscene due to scenes of two men kissing, the appearance of naked men, and sexual relations between men. 'Degrading...'",
  "candidate_translation": "Isn't Lebanon tolerant towards homosexuals?"
}

{
  "source_translation": "A large majority of the 2700 refugees who want to go to Austria, Germany, and other European countries reached Slovenia yesterday. Slovenian Prime Minister Miro Cerar stated that military units are on standby to cope with the influx of refugees. Cerar emphasized that they will continue to accept asylum seekers as long as Austria and Germany keep their borders open. Hungary announced that it closed its border with Croatia due to the failure of EU leaders to agree on a plan to stop the influx of refugees. The news also mentioned that Hungary had closed its border with Serbia, another route to Western Europe, last month. Throughout the day yesterday, hundreds of refugees in Croatia were transported by bus from the Serbian border to the Slovenian border. Most of the refugees made a weeks-long journey on foot through Greece, Macedonia, and Serbia to reach the Croatian border. After registering the refugees, Slovenian authorities arranged buses for them to cross into Austria. A UN spokesperson stated that most of the refugees in Slovenia are Syrian, Iraqi, and Afghan. Spokesperson Caroline van Buren said, \"They are fleeing from war. They are escaping to save their lives. Unlike other countries, Slovenia had time to prepare. It’s not perfect, but things are working.\" Croatia is an EU member. However, it is not in the Schengen Area like Slovenia or Hungary.",
  "candidate_translation": "Slovenia opened its border to refugees after Hungary closed its border with Croatia last night."
}

{
  "source_translation": "It was announced that the weapon was purchased by a private collector who called the auction company by phone, paying three times the estimated price. The small rusted pistol was found in 1965 by a farmer living near the village of Auvers-sur-Oise, where van Gogh spent his last days on the outskirts of Paris. The Dutch painter shot himself in the chest with a pistol after walking to a field near this village on July 27, 1890. The force of the gun was so limited that it took days for him to die from the wounds he sustained. The end of the Twitter post stated, '1 Van Gogh Institute: This tragedy is being commercialized.' About 70 years after his death, a rusted pistol was found in the same field behind the chateau where he stayed. Experts assessed that the gun could be the same one due to its age of 50 to 80 years. However, it has not been proven whether the found gun is the one van Gogh used to take his own life. The Van Gogh Institute criticized the auctioning of the gun as van Gogh's 'suicide weapon,' stating that 'this tragedy, which deserves more respect, is being commercialized.' The auction company, Art Auction, noted that while it is not possible to confirm the guns match, the overlapping dates strengthen theories in that direction.",
  "candidate_translation": "The pistol believed to be the one used by the famous Dutch painter Vincent van Gogh to commit suicide in 1890 was sold for 162,500 euros at an auction held in Paris, France."
}

{
  "source_translation": "Netflix announced that it has halted the production of the House of Cards series. Mexican actor Roberto Cavazos, who has appeared in many productions at London's Old Vic theatre, stated that Spacey continuously harassed young male actors during his tenure as the artistic director of the theatre from 2004 to 2015. In a note posted on Facebook, Cavazos said, \"Being a man under 30 was enough for Spacey to feel entitled to touch us.\" On Sunday, Kevin Spacey was accused of harassment by American actor Anthony Rapp. Rapp, known for his role in Star Trek: Discovery, claimed that he was harassed by Spacey, who was 26 at the time, at a party in 1986 when Rapp was 14 years old. Spacey, who also directed House of Cards, quickly released a statement regarding Rapp's allegations, stating that he did not remember the incident but sincerely apologized for his \"inappropriate drunken behavior\" as described. In the same statement, Spacey came out as gay, but this announcement was criticized as it was made in response to the harassment allegation. Following the claims and the resulting outrage, Netflix announced that it has suspended the production of the sixth season of House of Cards, in a joint statement with production company Media Rights Capital, describing the decision to suspend the production as \"the situation...\"",
  "candidate_translation": "Following harassment allegations against American actor Kevin Spacey, the filming of the House of Cards series, in which he starred, has been halted."
}

{
  "source_translation": "The cars purchased by the Dutch police can reach a speed of 100 kilometers in 5.5 seconds. To intervene more effectively with criminals, the Dutch police decided to establish a fleet of 'rapid intervention vehicles' (HMA) some time ago. For this purpose, an agreement was made with the Germany-based Audi company, and 70 Audi A6 3.0 TDI model cars were purchased. However, De Telegraaf, one of the leading newspapers in the Netherlands, documented that 40 of these vehicles are currently being stored. This is because there is not enough trained personnel who have received special driving training to operate these cars. According to the newspaper, police officers who will use these cars, which can reach 100 kilometers in 5.5 seconds, need to undergo special training. However, the police academy is unable to meet the demands for special driving training. In over a year, only a small number of personnel have been trained in advanced driving techniques. Since basic driving courses and training for arrest teams are conducted together at the academy, the HMA fleet will remain without drivers for a while longer. According to the newspaper, the 40 cars, worth approximately 5 million euros, will remain in storage for at least another year due to the lack of drivers. Following the media coverage of the news, former Formula 1 driver Guido van der Garde offered to assist police officers with advanced driving techniques if needed.",
  "candidate_translation": "The Dutch police are forced to store their luxury cars worth 5 million euros because they cannot find drivers to operate them."
}

{
  "source_translation": "After the meeting, CHP Chairman Kemal Kılıçdaroğlu criticized the RTÜK's decision to suspend the program and impose a fine on Habertürk television due to Mersin Deputy Ali Mahir Başarır's controversial remarks about the Turkish army, saying, \"This must be the legal reform they are talking about.\" He emphasized once again the importance of \"friends\": \"Together with our friends, we will bring democracy to this beautiful country.\" The recent visits among opposition parties continued with Kılıçdaroğlu's visit to his coalition partner, Democratic Party Chairman Gültekin Uysal. The increasing meeting traffic among opposition parties is interpreted in political circles as a message to keep the \"dialogue door open\" for future alliances. A senior CHP official expressed the significance of Kılıçdaroğlu's visit with the following words: \"We are visiting our friends. Ultimately, the components of democracy and those seeking justice in this country will come together. Turkey will evaluate those in favor of democracy against those in favor of a single leader. The Chairman is visiting all parties that demand democracy and justice.\" Kılıçdaroğlu, after the meeting with Gültekin Uysal, also made a statement to journalists regarding his party's Mersin Deputy Ali Mahir Başarır's remarks about Habertürk...",
  "candidate_translation": "CHP Chairman Kemal Kılıçdaroğlu visited his coalition partner, Democratic Party Chairman Gültekin Uysal."
}

{
  "source_translation": "Premier League leader Chelsea faces the Turkish champion tonight in the first leg of their last 16 clash. Former Manchester City coach Mancini noted that Chelsea, who have won the Champions League and Europa League in the last two seasons, are the favorites to advance. Mancini stated, \"They have great players who are used to matches like this.\" He believes there is an 80% chance they will progress. Despite Jose Mourinho's claim that his team is too young to win major tournaments, Mancini is convinced Chelsea has the ability to win a trophy this season. The Mancini-Mourinho rivalry flared up earlier this week when Mancini claimed he contributed to Inter's Champions League victory. Mourinho took over Inter after Mancini and won the Champions League with the Italian team. Currently the manager of Chelsea, Mourinho rejected the notion that Mancini had a role in that success, stating, \"Six of my eleven players were not in his squad. So his team would only play with five players in the tournament because I had only five players from his team.\" Mancini emphasized that former Chelsea forward Didier Drogba and Dutch midfielder Wesley Sneijder are crucial for Galatasaray's hopes of reaching the last eight for the second consecutive season. Tonight's match will not be Drogba's first against his former boss Mourinho.",
  "candidate_translation": "Galatasaray's coach Roberto Mancini acknowledged that Chelsea is a better team than them in the Champions League."
}

{
  "source_translation": "The symbolic clock is 2 minutes away from \"striking midnight.\" The \"Doomsday Clock\" is updated by scientists who are members of the Bulletin of the Atomic Scientists (BAS). Updated since 1947, the clock serves as a metaphor for how close humanity is to destroying the world. According to scientists, the world has become an increasingly \"dangerous\" place, and it has never been this close to \"doomsday\" since 1953. In 1953, after both the U.S. and Russia tested hydrogen bombs, the clock was moved forward again, marking 2 minutes to midnight. Last year, it was also moved forward by 30 seconds. What is the reason for this decision? The committee announcing the decision in Washington, D.C. stated that it was not an easy decision and that there is no single reason behind it. BAS President Rachel Bronson said that this year's discussions centered around nuclear issues. North Korea's nuclear tests, rising tensions in Korea, and the verbal war between the U.S. and North Korea have been the most concerning topics for scientists. BAS also noted that the U.S. strategy to increase nuclear spending is alarming. The rising tensions between Russia and the West were also factors influencing the decision. Scientists say that when the clock strikes midnight, it will signal the end of the world due to global threats like climate change and the struggles of international institutions fighting against them.",
  "candidate_translation": "The committee announcing the decision in Washington, D.C. stated that it was not an easy decision and that there is no single reason behind it. BAS President Rachel Bronson said that this year's discussions centered around nuclear issues."
}

{
  "source_translation": "An examination of brain scans of 638 individuals who have surpassed retirement age revealed that those who were physically active over a three-year period experienced less brain shrinkage. Scientists noted that these exercises do not need to be heavy or intense; walking a few times a week is sufficient. Another striking point in the study was that playing chess and meeting with friends did not show a direct contribution to preserving brain volume. Researchers found that when examining the white matter in the brain, the damage rate in individuals who exercised at age 70 was lower compared to those who did not. It was also discovered that the gray matter, which is the source of messages in the brain, was higher in those who exercised. Experts already knew that the human brain shrinks with age, and it is also known that this shrinkage leads to a decline in memory and cognitive power. Previous studies have shown that exercise reduces the risk of dementia. However, scientists have not yet been able to determine how exercise helps reduce brain shrinkage and the risk of dementia. It is also known that exercise increases blood circulation in the brain, along with the rest of the body. A study conducted by the Alzheimer's Research organization based in the UK found that exercise...",
  "candidate_translation": "A study conducted in the UK revealed that a lack of exercise prevents brain shrinkage."
}

{
  "source_translation": "After his candidacy was announced, Demirtaş held a press conference and stated, \"We will show during the campaign that we are not candidates for Çankaya alone, as individuals.\" He continued, \"I do not possess any special talent or power. I was nominated simply because a candidate needed to be shown.\" Demirtaş mentioned that they are asserting the claim of the oppressed, the marginalized, and the masses to govern themselves, stating that with his candidacy, they have already \"won for the people.\" He also expressed that the biggest deficiency in the presidential election is the absence of a female candidate among the nominees. For the presidential election, which will be put to a public vote for the first time in August, the Republican People's Party (CHP) and the Nationalist Movement Party (MHP) submitted their application for their joint candidate, Ekmeleddin İhsanoğlu, to the Speaker of the Grand National Assembly, Cemil Çiçek, on Sunday. President Abdullah Gül also announced yesterday that he would not run for Çankaya Köşkü again. The AKP candidate is expected to be announced on July 1. Deputy Prime Minister Bülent Arınç stated last Wednesday that \"their candidate is largely Prime Minister Recep Tayyip Erdoğan.\" Arınç added, \"If [the Prime Minister] is also willing, we will make this announcement on July 1...\"",
  "candidate_translation": "HDP's presidential candidate Selahattin Demirtaş was nominated regarding his candidacy."
}

{
  "source_translation": "Filiz Tutya is a 53-year-old textile worker who has been in the industry for 35 years, spending the last seven years at Bravo Tekstil. Recently, the name Bravo Tekstil became known in Turkey due to a campaign initiated by its workers. They attached labels to jackets, pants, sweaters, and shirts in many Zara stores in Istanbul, stating: \"I made the product you are about to buy, but I haven't received my payment! We produced for Zara for years. The factory closed overnight without paying our last three months' salaries and severance pay. Please tell Zara to pay us!\" Thousands supported the #BravoIscileriIcinAdalet hashtag on social media. An online petition has gathered over 270,000 signatures so far. Bravo Tekstil went bankrupt and closed suddenly in July 2016, with the owner disappearing. The company produced for international brands like Zara, Next, and Mango. Workers, who claim they did not receive their salaries during the bankruptcy process, are now demanding Zara to pay their three months' salaries and severance pay. Filiz Tutya, who last worked as the Quality Technical Manager at Bravo Tekstil, says, \"We had no other chance but this campaign: We will never...\"",
  "candidate_translation": "Workers from a factory supplying Zara in Turkey say, \"One day we came to the factory. One day we had a voice. But we have no employer. We are not receiving our payments. They should address our grievances.\""
}

{
  "source_translation": "After the meeting, CHP Chairman Kemal Kılıçdaroğlu criticized the RTÜK's decision to suspend the program and impose a fine on Habertürk television due to Mersin Deputy Ali Mahir Başarır's controversial remarks about the Turkish army, saying, \"I guess this is the legal reform they are talking about.\" He emphasized once again the importance of \"friends\": \"Together with our friends, we will bring democracy to this beautiful country.\" The recent visits among opposition parties continued with Kılıçdaroğlu's visit to his coalition partner, Democratic Party Chairman Gültekin Uysal. The increasing meeting traffic among opposition parties is interpreted in political circles as a message to keep the \"dialogue door open\" for future alliances. A senior CHP official expressed the significance of Kılıçdaroğlu's visit with the following words: \"We are visiting our friends. Ultimately, the components of democracy and those seeking justice in this country will come together. Turkey will evaluate those in favor of democracy against those in favor of a single leader. The Chairman is visiting all parties that demand democracy and justice.\" The emphasis on \"democracy with friends\" was reiterated by Kılıçdaroğlu during a statement to journalists after the meeting with Gültekin Uysal regarding the remarks of his party's Mersin Deputy Ali Mahir Başarır about Habertürk...",
  "candidate_translation": "CHP Chairman Kemal Kılıçdaroğlu reacted to the sale of the tank pallet factory, one of the most critical periods in Turkish politics."
}

{
  "source_translation": "In the U.S., both the S&P 500 index and the Dow Jones index saw a 7% drop in the morning, leading to automatic trading halts for the second time this week for 15 minutes. Yesterday, the Dow Jones index had already dropped by 1,500 points, or 5.8%. In the first half of the day, the London Stock Exchange's FTSE 100 index recorded its largest drop in seven years with a 5.7% decline. The biggest losses on the London Stock Exchange were seen in travel companies, with IAG's shares down 9% and Tui losing 10%. Previously, there were significant drops in Asian markets, with the Tokyo Stock Exchange's Nikkei 225 index closing down 4.4%. In Asia, the Hong Kong Stock Exchange fell by 3.6%, and the Shanghai Stock Exchange dropped by 1.9%. Oil prices also fell by 4%, with Brent crude oil priced at $34.34. The cryptocurrency Bitcoin, which was trading at $7,859 last night, dropped 15% to $6,600 today. The effects of the coronavirus were also felt in Borsa Istanbul, where the BIST 100 index fell by 4.36% to 96,565.07 points in the first half of the day. The index had closed the previous day at 100,966 points with a 0.10% loss. While pharmaceutical companies saw a nearly 19% increase due to expectations of rising consumption, sports clubs' shares faced risks due to matches being played without spectators.",
  "candidate_translation": "In Europe, stock markets are experiencing declines following travel restrictions imposed by many countries due to the coronavirus and U.S. President Donald Trump's decision to halt entries from Europe to the U.S."
}

{
  "source_translation": "Are you tired, suffering from migraines, or feeling depressed? Then Isaac Pulvermacher's 'hydro-electric belt' might offer a solution! The device delivers an electric current to the relevant area through electrodes at both ends of the belt. Featured at the first World Fair in London in 1851, this device quickly reached annual sales of 50,000 units. Even the famous English writer Charles Dickens showed interest in this device. While suffering from severe leg pain during his reading tours in the 1860s, he purchased the electric belt in 1870 on a recommendation. Dickens likely used the electric belt in this way for his leg pain. According to medical historian Robert K Waits, 'when this belt was tested, the patient was not alive enough to report the result.' Indeed, Dickens's last letter was to inform the Pulvermacher company that he had received the device. Today, scientists resort to electrotherapy to alleviate certain ailments. Despite its fame, the Pulvermacher belt was not the first device to use electricity. In 48 BC, the doctor of Roman Emperor Claudius, Largus, attempted to treat migraines by placing an electric ray on the head. Although Largus may not have yet discovered the power of electricity, in the 18th century, scientists like Benjamin Franklin began to control this energy and understand its effects on the body. With the invention of the battery in the 19th century, this... [repetition continues]",
  "candidate_translation": "Can a person give themselves an electric current?"
}

{
  "source_translation": "According to a report by Today newspaper published in the USA, Sierra Strangfeld learned that her baby had 'trisomy 18' syndrome at the 20th week of her pregnancy. However, Strangfeld and her husband decided not to terminate the pregnancy after learning that their baby would not live long after birth. 'We never thought about terminating the pregnancy.' Two months before the birth, as the risk of the baby dying became apparent, Strangfeld underwent a cesarean section. The baby, named Samuel, was born weighing 650 grams and died three hours later. Strangfeld, who has an 18-month-old daughter, said, 'We never thought about terminating the pregnancy. We wanted to welcome this precious gift, just like all babies, in the best way possible.' After Samuel's death, Strangfeld donated 14 kilos of breast milk to a milk bank called 'NICU.' Regarding her donation, Sierra Strangfeld said, 'We had nothing we could do to prevent Samuel's death. But there are things we can do for other babies,' and expressed her desire to establish a foundation for 'trisomy 18.' Trisomy 18 syndrome, also known as Edward Syndrome, is a chromosomal disorder caused by the presence of three copies of the 18th chromosome in cells. According to the UK National Health Service, 75% of babies with this syndrome do not survive more than 24 hours after birth. The percentage of babies living beyond one year with this syndrome is around five percent.",
  "candidate_translation": "Sierra Strangfeld donated breast milk that her baby had accumulated for 3 hours."
}

{
  "source_translation": "Cameramen capturing the conflicts in Syria from the Turkish border must ensure that the identification and interpretation of the facts are done in a way that does not favor any side of the conflict. In the UK, the BBC is considered a 'national broadcaster' by many, and it faces pressure to adopt a patriotic language in conflicts, using phrases like 'our soldiers' when referring to British troops and interpreting the war from a British perspective. However, what makes the BBC a reliable news source is its neutrality. Therefore, the BBC always uses terms like 'British forces', 'American soldiers', 'Pakistani army', and 'Turkish troops'. All broadcasters must show sensitivity, especially when discussing casualties. No news should endanger the safety of soldiers. There are also many anti-war individuals among viewers and readers, who know that certain military details will not be published until the possibility of affecting the conflict is over. However, if for any reason the news is censored or not fully conveyed, the reporter must clearly explain this and the reasons behind it. Known and unknown facts, as well as unanswered questions, should be honestly communicated to the audience. Casualties resulting from military actions, the numbers of those who lost their lives or were injured, or...",
  "candidate_translation": "As the conflicts in Syria escalate, anti-war protests are increasing in Turkey."
}

{
  "source_translation": "The news agency reported that Syrian forces have made contact with soldiers defending the airbase and have neutralized a large number of militants. The airbase had been under attack from ISIS for about two years. Meanwhile, in Latakia, the coastal city in western Syria that has been relatively unaffected by the country's conflicts, at least 22 people were killed in mortar attacks. Syrian state television reported that the mortars hitting residential areas injured 57 others. This was the largest attack to occur in the Alawite city, which is the hometown of President Bashar al-Assad and under the control of the Syrian army. Footage broadcasted by state television showed vehicles on fire and some vehicles hit by shrapnel. The Syrian army had launched a new operation against opposition groups in the towns surrounding Latakia, with Russian warplanes providing aerial support. No explanation has been given regarding which group carried out the mortar attack in Latakia, and no group has claimed responsibility yet. Reports are also coming in about attacks on the army near the capital, Damascus. The Associated Press reported that opposition groups have shelled some neighborhoods in Damascus, but...",
  "candidate_translation": "The Syrian army fulfilled the siege by ISIS, as the Syrian army completed its siege."
}

{
  "source_translation": "The actions are being carried out to protest layoffs and mandatory relocations in the public sector. On the first day of a five-day strike series, teachers went on strike today. Civil servants also called for a two-day strike on Wednesday. This strike is supported by universities, doctors, and lawyers. The layoffs are part of the bailout conditions imposed by the country's international creditors. These parties will meet in Athens to discuss the next loan installment. So far, Greece has received two aid packages totaling 240 billion euros. An additional 10 billion euros is needed to cover the funding gap. Strong resistance was met when a group of school security guards clashed with riot police outside the Ministry of Administrative Reform in Athens on Monday morning. Security forces used tear gas to disperse the protesters. Three people were hospitalized due to minor injuries. Officials from the European Commission, the European Central Bank, and the International Monetary Fund will gather in Athens this week to finalize the next 1 billion euro loan. In exchange for the loans, Prime Minister Antonis Samaras agreed to reduce the salaries of 25,000 civil servants this year before any transfers or layoffs. BBC reporter Mark Lowen in Athens notes that for the first time under the Greek constitution, public sector workers will lose their jobs. By the end of 2014, 15,000 public...",
  "candidate_translation": "Teachers in Greece have started a strike."
}

{
  "source_translation": "However, he did not provide details on who he met with from the US administration or how a program would be prepared. Mazlum Kobani stated that 'Joe Biden's election as President of the United States has given him greater hope for a realistic solution to the Syrian crisis' and noted that coordination with Russia continues, adding, 'It has always been challenging to maintain balance in our relations with Washington and Moscow.' Mazlum Abdi, also known as Mazlum Kobani, was a prominent figure during Turkey's Operation Peace Spring in the region controlled by the SDF in October 2019. Former US President Donald Trump thanked Kobani several times during and after the operation, which drew reactions in Ankara, where President Recep Tayyip Erdoğan stated, 'America must hand this man over to us.' McGurk frequently visited Syria during the Obama administration to meet with SDF-linked groups. Biden appointed Brett McGurk, the special representative for the anti-ISIS coalition during Barack Obama's presidency, as 'Coordinator for the Middle East and North Africa' at the White House. McGurk's decisive role in supporting the SDF in the fight against ISIS also faced backlash in Ankara. Turkey has reacted against the People's Protection Units (YPG), which form the basis of the SDF, due to their alleged connections with the PKK.",
  "candidate_translation": "Speaking to the UK-based news site al-Maghafi, Mazlum Kobani stated that a joint program is being prepared with the new US administration for the Syrian Democratic Forces (SDF) and mentioned that the Trump administration had requested support for the SDF."
}

{
  "source_translation": "In an attack targeting a police convoy in the Essa Nagri area of Karachi, Chaudri Aslam Khan, who was at the forefront of the city's counter-terrorism operations, and at least two others were killed. Chaudri Aslam Khan had previously survived several assassination attempts. The Pakistani Taliban claimed responsibility for today's attack. A Taliban spokesperson stated that Khan was targeted for 'killing, torturing, and injuring Taliban members.' An explosive-laden vehicle collided with Khan's convoy. Photos from the scene show that many vehicles were completely destroyed, and nearby buildings were also damaged. Pakistan's Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif condemned the attack on security official Chaudri Aslam Khan. Reporters note that Khan is a well-known figure in Karachi. Since 2008, Khan's unit has led to the detention of dozens of militants planning attacks in Pakistan and Afghanistan, including those who could be suicide bombers.",
  "candidate_translation": "In a bomb attack in Karachi, Pakistan, one of the city's top security officials was killed."
}

{
  "source_translation": "Hurricane Matthew is the strongest hurricane to hit the Caribbean in the last 10 years. The United Nations stated that it could take days to understand the extent of the damage caused by the hurricane in Haiti. The death toll has exceeded 800. Carlos Veloso, head of the World Food Program, mentioned that some towns can only be reached by sea or air. The hurricane, which also affected Cuba, is moving towards the eastern coast of the United States via the Bahamas. A Haitian official speaking to the French news agency AFP reported that more than 50 people have died in the southern town of Roche-a-Bateau. It was noted that 80% of the houses in Jeremie, the largest city in the region, were completely destroyed. In Sud department, 30,000 homes were damaged. The photo shows Haitians carrying a coffin. Although the hurricane struck Haiti earlier in the week, the scale of the disaster is just emerging due to communication being cut off, especially in the southeast of the country. The storm's speed was reported to have reached 230 kilometers per hour over Haiti. BBC reporter Tony Brown in the area reports that Haitians are trying to repair their destroyed homes, and no aid has come from the government or military. UN: 350,000 people need humanitarian assistance. The United Nations announced that 350,000 people in the country need humanitarian aid. Reports are coming from the Bahamas of uprooted trees and power outages, but there is no information on casualties yet.",
  "candidate_translation": "The death toll in Haiti is rising due to Hurricane Matthew, which struck the Caribbean."
}

{
  "source_translation": "Today, some tribes that still practice hunting and gathering continue to remain naked. This shows that clothing is not essential for survival. So when did we start wearing clothes? We lack data to show when early humans stopped being naked and began covering their bodies with animal hides and skins, as clothing decays before it can fossilize. Instead, anthropologists try to determine the timeline through indirect methods. A study on lice conducted in 2011 revealed that the origins of clothing date back 170,000 years. Researchers believe that the human louse and the clothing louse diverged as species around that time. Without hair, there was clothing. At that time, the ancestor of modern humans, Homo sapiens, had emerged in Africa. They had less body hair. In contrast, earlier hominins were hairier. At a certain stage of their development, early humans felt the need to wear clothing. Some experts think that this need arose to compensate for hair loss. The minimal clothing worn by some tribes, like the Nuer in Sudan, who still practice hunting and gathering, suggests that covering up may not only be for protection but could also indicate the emergence of a sense of shame. However, there is no data to prove this. Other hunter-gatherer communities, like the Fuegian tribe in South America, also show that they sometimes wore simple clothing but also roamed naked.",
  "candidate_translation": "Clothing is an important part of human history. So, when did early humans start to wear clothes?"
}

{
  "source_translation": "According to a Reuters report, Anton Moskvin, the deputy chairman of Rosatom, stated that the signing of the nuclear power plant agreement will take place by the end of the year. Speaking during his visit to the United Arab Emirates (UAE), Moskvin expressed that if the agreement is signed by the end of 2015, the construction of the first reactor of the nuclear plant to be established in the northern Egyptian city of Dabaa could also be completed by 2022. Moskvin said, \"The sooner we sign, the sooner we finish,\" and added, \"We can start the site assessment next year, and we will see how early we can begin construction on-site.\" Egypt has been planning to establish a plant in Dabaa, located in Matrouh province, since 1981. Following the Chernobyl disaster in 1986, Cairo decided to halt its nuclear program but announced in 2006 that it would revive it. Plans to tender the construction of the nuclear plant began after the ousting of former President Hosni Mubarak in 2011. Discussions are also ongoing with Saudi Arabia. In February of this year, President Abdel Fattah el-Sisi announced that a memorandum of understanding had been signed with Russia for the project. The Dabaa nuclear power plant, which is planned to have four reactors, is expected to be completed by 2025. Rosatom is the only company negotiating with Egypt for the nuclear project. Moskvin noted, \"About 200 people from both sides meet every month to discuss commercial, technical, and other issues...\"",
  "candidate_translation": "Discussions between Russia and Egypt regarding the nuclear power plant to be established in northern Egypt have reached the final stage."
}

{
  "source_translation": "Yenigün was first suspended from his school and then dismissed after signing the Academics for Peace declaration. He was in the United States, where he had been for a long time, giving conferences during the July 15 coup attempt. During this period, when passports were canceled and international departures were highly controlled, he canceled his short visit to Turkey and headed to the university in Germany that had accepted him. Yenigün, who received a scholarship in Islamic Studies at the Free University of Berlin, is now drawing attention to a changing situation. Years ago, Yenigün, who studied in Turkey and later completed his doctorate in the U.S. before returning to the country, states that Turkey used to have an appeal for those studying abroad to return, but this has now changed: 'Generally, citizens of other countries who go to the U.S. for their doctorate tend to stay there. Turkey had a special situation, a situation unique to academics, which was to return. Turkey was a country that could attract its citizens back, regardless of the circumstances. This situation has changed.' After the coup attempt, 15 universities were closed by decrees. The highest number of applications to the Scholar Rescue Fund, established by the International Institute of Education (IIE), came from Turkey, as noted by Sarah Willcox, the director of the fund, who participated in an event in September.",
