{
  "source_translation": "Lawyer Trịnh Văn Long stated that Mr. Trần has not eaten since being taken to Thổ Thành prison on Wednesday. He said his client wants to \"protest the death of justice.\" Mr. Trần, who has not yet been formally charged, claims he is being punished by his successor for opposing closer ties with Beijing. However, this accusation has been denied by both the Chinese government and the current Taiwanese President Ma Ying-jeou of the Kuomintang. Mr. Trần has criticized the Kuomintang's China policy since leaving office in May after eight years as president. He was handcuffed and detained by prosecutors on Tuesday and then imprisoned on Wednesday. According to AP, the lawyer said Mr. Trần \"opposes the authoritarian regime in Taiwan and the communist regime, and he wants sovereignty for Taiwan.\" The lawyer added that his client is currently in a \"temporary stable\" condition. Mr. Trần could be held in custody for a maximum of four months. He and his family have faced numerous corruption allegations since 2006, when his son-in-law was convicted of insider trading and sentenced to seven years in prison. These allegations have severely impacted the reputation of the DPP, now the opposition party, and could pose challenges for the party in next year's local elections. Taiwan separated from the mainland and has been led by the Kuomintang since 1949 after the civil war. The...",
