{
  "source_translation": "American scientists Mario R. Capecchi and Oliver Smithies, along with British partner Sir Martin J. Evans, made a groundbreaking discovery in the field of genetic research. This breakthrough led to a technology commonly known as 'targeted gene selection.' It allows researchers to inhibit certain genes, enabling them to understand the roles of these genes in health and various diseases. This method allows for the recreation of certain human diseases in mice by introducing genetic changes into the mouse genome. The Nobel Committee stated that this discovery has provided new insights into conditions such as cancer and heart disease. For instance, scientists can now understand how diseases can affect healthy individuals. This genetic research technology also helps in understanding the aging process in humans, as well as how a fetus develops in the womb. The Nobel Committee noted that this technology is now used across nearly all fields of biomedical research.",
