{
  "source_translation": "The White House accused journalist Acosta of having \"put his hands on\" an intern during a press conference. CNN's White House correspondent Jim Acosta had his \"hard pass,\" a press credential, revoked last week, just hours after he had a heated exchange with President Trump. CNN claimed this violated the constitutional rights of both the network and Acosta. A lawsuit, filed in Washington DC on Tuesday, November 12, names the president and his senior aides as defendants. Among those named are Chief of Staff John Kelly and White House Press Secretary Sarah Sanders, who stated that Acosta's unacceptable behavior was the reason for the revocation of his press credentials. On Tuesday, Sanders said in a statement that Acosta was one of nearly 50 CNN hard pass holders, adding that this was \"not the first time this reporter has refused to yield the floor to other reporters.\" \"The White House cannot have an orderly and fair press conference when a reporter acts in this way, which is both inappropriate and unprofessional,\" the statement read. President Donald Trump clashed with CNN reporter Jim Acosta at the press conference on November 7. \"The First Amendment is not being upheld when a...",
