{
  "source_translation": "Abdul Hadi Awang declared at the annual PAS party conference that he accepts Anwar as a leader. Last September, Anwar's conviction was overturned, and he was released after serving six years in prison. Hadi's public support for Anwar Ibrahim is a clear indication that the former prime minister remains a key figure in Malaysian politics. The leader of the conservative Islamic party told supporters that Anwar's credibility could help expand their appeal. However, Hadi vowed not to abandon commitments to an Islamic state. Yet, this very commitment has previously caused rifts in opposition party alliances. Over 40% of Malaysians are non-Muslims and have abandoned parties that previously allied with PAS in past elections. Last year, even Muslim voters punished PAS for focusing on religion rather than everyday concerns like rural poverty and corruption. Anwar's persuasive ability may not be enough to unite the opposition and voters if PAS does not soften its stance. Currently, the former deputy prime minister has not responded to this call. Many here believe that Anwar Ibrahim still harbors ambitions for leadership...",
