{
  "source_translation": "Vietnamese Prime Minister Nguyen Xuan Phuc (right) and Chinese Premier Li Keqiang (left) in Beijing in 2016. The Ministry of Planning and Investment has warned the Vietnamese government about preferential loans and official development assistance from China. The ministry stated that many such projects are poorly managed while Hanoi has to spend more than expected, according to the Nikkei Asian Review. In a report sent to Prime Minister Nguyen Xuan Phuc, cited by Vietnamese media, the ministry noted that projects funded by Chinese loans generally have less favorable borrowing conditions compared to loans from other countries. According to VnExpress, the Ministry of Planning and Investment emphasized that the government should reconsider its direction towards borrowing preferential credit from China. Vietnamese reactions regarding train tickets printed with Chinese characters. Vietnam's economy is at risk if it relies too much on exports to China. The case of the nine-dash line T-shirt: 'Vietnam reserves its anger.' Loans and aid from China have an annual interest rate of 3%, higher than Japan's 0.4%-1.2%, South Korea's 0%-2%, and India's 1.75%. Additionally, borrowing from China incurs a commitment fee of 0.5% and a management fee of 0.5%, while the loan term and grace period are shorter than other capital markets, at 15 and 5 years respectively. Preferential credit loans are provided through the China Eximbank, according to VnExpress. Many projects under Beijing's ODA program are progressing slowly and of poor quality, leading to increased investment to address issues arising...",
