{
  "source_translation": "Simon Cheng believes he would face danger if he returned to Hong Kong. Simon Cheng, a Hong Kong citizen, was detained for 15 days during a business trip to mainland China last August. Beijing accused him of inciting political unrest amid anti-government protests in Hong Kong. Cheng denied the allegations, telling the BBC that he was beaten and forced to sign false confessions while in custody. British government sources stated at the time that they found Cheng's claims credible. A pro-democracy advocate, Cheng expressed that returning to Hong Kong is too dangerous, fearing he could be arrested and taken back to mainland China again. In June, UK Foreign Secretary Dominic Raab stated that China had not provided a 'proper response' to the UK's inquiries about the incident. Cheng was granted asylum on June 26. In a press conference on Wednesday, he mentioned that he believes he is the first person in Hong Kong with a British National Overseas (BNO) passport to receive political asylum. 'I am grateful for the determination and courage of the British government in rescuing British citizens,' he wrote on Facebook. 'I also hope that the situation... [repetition continues]",
