{
  "source_translation": "The prison on Nusakambangan Island. United Nations human rights officials have expressed concern over these executions, urging Jakarta to end 'unjust' death sentences. The identities of the prisoners have not been disclosed, but among them are citizens from Nigeria, Zimbabwe, Pakistan, and India. They are to be executed at the prison on Nusakambangan Island. The prisoners have been informed of this, according to Indonesian law, and could be executed early on July 29. Attorney General Muhammad Prasetyo stated that 14 death row inmates are in solitary confinement. The executions are expected to take place by July 31 at the latest. Zeid Ra'ad al-Hussein, the UN High Commissioner for Human Rights, expressed concern that the prisoners have not received fair trials and called on Indonesia to halt the executions. Relatives of the death row inmates for drug trafficking in Indonesia stated, 'The increasing abuse of the death penalty in Indonesia is alarming, and I urge Jakarta to immediately end these unjust sentences that are inconsistent with human rights.' He added, 'The death penalty is not an effective deterrent compared to other penalties and does not protect people from drug abuse.' Mr. Hussein called on Indonesia to restore the moratorium on the death penalty that was lifted three years ago. Relatives visited the prisoners on July 27 at Nusakambangan. Indonesian law is among the strictest in the world regarding drug crime penalties, and the execution of 14 drug traffickers - most...",
