{
  "source_translation": "Colonel Le Trong Nghia, a victim in the recent 'Anti-Party Revisionism' case, passed away on February 22, 2015. The BBC and guests discussed whether to publicly reopen the case files of the 'Anti-Party Revisionism' case, which is believed to have many signs of 'wrongful conviction' and 'lack of clarity', following the death of a 'victim' from the case nearly half a century ago. This victim was Colonel Le Trong Nghia, former Director of the North Vietnamese Military Intelligence, and former secretary to General Vo Nguyen Giap. A document purported to be a draft 'Will' of Colonel Nghia, who died on Sunday, February 22, 2015, states that he requested the Party and Government, specifically the Politburo and the Party's Secretariat, to 'clear his name' and 'restore his honor'. He also asserted that he was not a 'spy' or 'traitor' but was implicated in the anti-Party revisionism case because he was a subordinate of General Giap. Several questions were raised by the BBC and guests in this week's discussion: What should be done about the anti-Party revisionism case? Is it time to reopen the files to understand the causes and motives of the incident, to examine whether this was a wrongful conviction, or even a case fabricated for political purposes? If this was entirely a 'fake' case, constructed with political intent, not just limited to 'internal struggles for power', but even related to 'foreign policy', relations with China, or foreign countries at that time of the Communist Party, then who...",
