{
  "source_translation": "The image of a coffin placed right at the entrance of the Pacific Crystal textile company in July. Behind it is a tent set up by the people of Hai Duong to protest. Meanwhile, local newspaper Hai Duong reported that authorities 'have done a good job of propaganda, mobilization, and explanation, so the clearance did not meet with public opposition.' Hundreds of residents in Lai Vu commune, Kim Thanh district, Hai Duong province have been setting up tents in front of the Lai Vu industrial zone for over 5 months, accusing the Hong Kong Pacific Crystal company of secretly discharging foul waste for more than two years. Some residents of Lai Vu told the BBC that for over 5 months, dozens of police and local authorities have continuously come to try to prevent them from setting up tents in the industrial zone; however, the peak of tension occurred on Monday afternoon, September 25. Reuters quoted a resident, Bui Van Nguyet, stating that 500 police 'used water cannons and electric batons to disperse about 200 residents.' The residents placed gasoline-soaked bottles to block the entrance to the Pacific Crystal textile company in protest against the company's waste discharge into the Lai Vu area. Another resident named Sim told the BBC that by around 3 PM, the residents were pushed out of the Lai Vu industrial zone, with two arrests and many injuries. 'We were very upset and went to the commune to demand the release of the detainees and take the injured to the hospital, but they...",
