{
  "source_translation": "Lopetegui has been coaching Spain since 2016. The events unfolded just two days before their first match in the World Cup against Portugal. BBC Game: Guess the 2018 World Cup champion. What are the chances for Asian teams at the 2018 World Cup? Fernando Hierro will temporarily lead the team at the World Cup. On Tuesday, European champions Real Madrid officially announced a three-year contract with coach Lopetegui following the resignation of his predecessor, Zinedine Zidane. Now, the Spanish Football Federation (RFEF) has announced that they have decided to dismiss the 51-year-old coach, stating that \"RFEF did not receive any information\" regarding the contract signing. RFEF President Luis Rubiales said, \"I know this is a sensitive situation, and whatever decision I make will be criticized. But I assure you, this will make us stronger. I greatly admire Julen; he is a great coach, which makes my decision even harder.\" According to Spanish media, the president was very angry upon learning the news and interrupted a meeting at FIFA to fly to the team's headquarters in Russia to investigate the matter. Many team members, including captain Sergio Ramos, have advised the president to postpone the dismissal until after the World Cup to ensure the best state for the entire team. It seems Mr. Luis...",
  "candidate_translation": "Spain has sacked coach Julen Lopetegui just two days before the team enters the 2018 World Cup finals."
}

{
  "source_translation": "Goalkeeper Văn Lâm stood out in the quarterfinal match on January 24, where Ritsu Doan scored the only goal for Japan in the 57th minute. In the 24th minute, Japan scored from a corner kick, but referee Mohammed Abdulla Hassan Mohamed disallowed the goal after VAR indicated a handball by a Japanese player. Goalkeeper Đặng Văn Lâm made several crucial saves for Vietnam. However, Vietnam also had clear chances to score in the first half, forcing goalkeeper Shuichi Gonda to showcase his skills against Phan Văn Đức and Nguyễn Quang Hải. Sports commentator Quang Huy assessed the quarterfinal match against Japan. Ten minutes into the second half, VAR played a key role again by determining that Bùi Tiến Dũng committed a foul in the penalty area. Ritsu Doan scored the only goal, although goalkeeper Văn Lâm guessed the direction of the ball correctly. Despite their efforts, Vietnam ultimately could not overcome one of the tournament favorites, allowing Japan to advance to the semifinals. The first half was balanced. What transpired in the first 45 minutes might lead one to believe this was a battle between equals, rather than between a Japan that has won the tournament four times and Vietnam, which has only reached the quarterfinals for the second time, between a team that reached the Round of 16 in the 2018 World Cup and a footballing nation where the World Cup remains a distant dream. Japan had superior ball possession (68% to 31%), but Vietnam had more shots on target (3 to 2).",
  "candidate_translation": "Japan advanced to the semifinals after narrowly defeating Vietnam 1-0 at Al Maktoum Stadium in Dubai on January 24."
}

{
  "source_translation": "Mr. Nguyen Viet Dung, known on social media as Dung Phi Ho, has been detained and prosecuted under Article 245 for 'causing public disorder' since late April 2015. He was arrested after participating in a march to protect green trees in Hanoi on April 12. He was described as wearing a t-shirt with the emblem of the Republic of Vietnam and the English phrase meaning 'The people are not afraid of the government; only the government is afraid of the people' on the back. On October 7, lawyer Tran Thu Nam, one of three lawyers (along with lawyers Vo An Don and Le Van Luan) representing Mr. Dung, told the BBC that an investigation conclusion regarding the 'causing public disorder' case against Nguyen Viet Dung has been reached. 'However, since I have not been consulted on the investigation conclusion, I cannot comment on this case. I can only say that the trial will take place in the next two months. The sentence for Mr. Dung will depend on the trial's developments,' Mr. Nam said. 'He has matured and has his own ideals.' In a conversation with the BBC on October 7, Mr. Nguyen Viet Hung, Dung's father, shared that during the five months his son has been detained, the family has visited six times but has not been able to meet him, only sending supplies. 'I hope my son will receive a light sentence because Dung is still very young. I do not understand the law and what Dung has done, so I was angry at first. But later, I accepted it because Dung has matured and has his own ideals.'",
  "candidate_translation": "One of the three lawyers for Nguyen Viet Dung has been prosecuted for 'causing public disorder.'"
}

{
  "source_translation": "In a meeting in 2014, Mr. Obama and Ms. Suu Kyi discussed the National League for Democracy (NLD) winning more than two-thirds of the seats needed to choose a president, ending decades of military rule. Ms. Suu Kyi's party gained control of both the upper and lower houses of Myanmar's parliament, according to the election commission. However, a quarter of the parliamentary seats were reserved for the military, meaning this faction would still have significant influence. Myanmar's constitution states that anyone with children holding foreign citizenship cannot hold the presidency. Ms. Suu Kyi, who has two sons with British citizenship, stated that she would ultimately lead the country. U.S. President Obama called Ms. Suu Kyi to congratulate her and her party, expressing hope that the election results would lead to a 'more peaceful and prosperous future.' Earlier, British Prime Minister David Cameron and U.S. Senator John Kerry issued statements praising the election process. Mr. Obama also directly acknowledged the 'success of the National League for Democracy' and praised Ms. Suu Kyi for her 'tireless efforts and sacrifices over many years to promote an inclusive, peaceful, and democratic Burma'—using another name for Myanmar in his commendation. Mr. Obama, who visited Myanmar twice during his presidency, expressed hope that the official election results would meet the expectations of all parties. The leader of Myanmar's military, General Min Aung Hlaing, stated that the military...",
  "candidate_translation": "The National League for Democracy (NLD) led by Aung San Suu Kyi has won the Myanmar election, according to results announced by the country's election commission."
}

{
  "source_translation": "This collection of wine was acquired during Jacques Chirac's time as mayor of Paris, featuring many rare bottles of champagne and Bordeaux valued at thousands of dollars. Chirac held the mayoral office from 1977 to 1995. The new socialist mayor has decided to sell all this wine to contribute to the public fund. French President Jacques Chirac was known for his refined taste, especially in gastronomy. While mayor, he often hosted lavish banquets. He and his wife spent about $600 daily on food and drinks. It’s no surprise that his wine cellar was filled with exquisite, expensive wines. Current Paris mayor Bertrand Delanoe ordered the sale of this wine after discovering many bottles were too valuable to be used for city banquets. The starting price for most of this wine is $750 per bottle, but some, like the 1990 Chateau Petrus, can reach $2,700. However, Chirac has since switched to drinking beer, so he may not be too upset about his wine cellar being liquidated.",
  "candidate_translation": "Mr. Chirac, the former French president, was the mayor of Paris from 1977 to 1995. He was a connoisseur, especially of wine. While mayor, he often hosted lavish parties. He and his wife spent $600 daily on food and drinks."
}

{
  "source_translation": "Mrs. Bhutto's party has not yet participated in street protests but is expected to take to the streets on Friday. However, the mayor of Rawalpindi has stated that he will prevent that march. A senior official in President Pervez Musharraf's party indicated that the state of emergency would last two or three weeks. Yet, a BBC reporter noted that Musharraf's party was sending mixed signals. Chaudhry Shujaat Hussain, president of the Pakistan Muslim League, told the Dawn newspaper: 'I am sure this situation will end within two to three weeks as President Pervez Musharraf has acknowledged the consequences of a prolonged state of emergency.' However, there are differing opinions within General Musharraf's party. Some members support holding the scheduled parliamentary elections in mid-January, while others want to postpone them. Mrs. Benazir Bhutto is currently in Islamabad discussing with other opposition leaders, although some have been arrested. The Alliance for the Restoration of Democracy, a religious political coalition, is present, while former Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif's PML-N party has refused to participate. So far, opposition parties have not mobilized their supporters for street protests, which mainly consist of lawyers and human rights activists. Hundreds of protesters have been arrested...",
  "candidate_translation": "The main opposition parties in Pakistan have agreed to cooperate to oppose the state of emergency declared by President Pervez Musharraf."
}

{
  "source_translation": "The UN Committee on the Rights of the Child urgently requested the Vatican to open its files on child sexual abusers as well as the priests and bishops who cover up their crimes. In a report released today, February 5, 2014, the Committee also criticized the Holy See for its attitude towards homosexuals, contraception, and abortion methods. The Committee called on the Vatican to reform its policies to ensure that children's rights are respected and that children have access to healthcare services. According to AFP, the UN Committee's recommendations are not binding. However, the UN can request the Vatican to implement these recommendations and report back in 2014. The Holy See has been 14 years late in submitting its most recent report. Last month, Vatican representatives were questioned for an entire day about issues related to the implementation of the UN Convention on the Rights of the Child. So far, the Holy See has often rotated the assignments of priests and bishops accused of child sexual abuse, including boys and girls, rather than reporting them to local authorities where the incidents occurred. In February 2012, Marie Collins, a victim of clerical abuse in Ireland, urged the Pope to ask victims for forgiveness as the Vatican continues to withhold records of child rape or abuse cases that occurred in dioceses in Europe and North America for decades. Nevertheless, nearing...",
  "candidate_translation": "The UN Committee has condemned the Vatican for child rape cases within its jurisdiction."
}

{
  "source_translation": "When this decision was made public, it was perhaps the first time the Bush administration had taken action to label a military branch of a sovereign nation as a terrorist organization. By designating Iran's Islamic Revolutionary Guard Corps (IRGC) as a 'terrorist organization,' the Bush administration sent a clear message to governments around the world not to engage, militarily or commercially, with the IRGC. For a long time, the Bush administration had accused the elite unit of the IRGC of supplying weapons and training to militia groups in Iraq. The IRGC has also been mentioned as having assisted other organizations deemed terrorist, such as Hamas and Hezbollah. In Iran, the IRGC is a significant economic and political force. The U.S. hopes that by placing the IRGC on the list of terrorist organizations, it will cut off international funding flowing into the IRGC's projects and disrupt this branch's business plans. A U.S. official told the BBC that the decision to label the IRGC as a terrorist organization was presented to the highest levels of the U.S. power structure and would soon be announced. Additionally, through the mechanism of the UN Security Council, the Bush administration has also applied further pressure on Iran to prevent its nuclear weapons development plans.",
  "candidate_translation": "The U.S. has designated Iran's military as a terrorist organization."
}

