{
  "source_translation": "In a meeting on Monday, the Board of Governors consisting of 35 countries from the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA), an organization established by the UN to monitor nuclear safety, agreed to this decision. The return of international inspectors to North Korea is a crucial condition in an agreement reached last February aimed at closing the Yongbyon nuclear reactor. In exchange, Pyongyang will receive economic aid and fuel shipments. The first delivery, a shipment of fuel oil, has already left a port in the south and is expected to arrive in North Korea by the end of this week. The agreement to close the IAEA Board of Governors in a special session in Vienna, the capital of Austria, has approved sending a team of inspectors back to North Korea. The cost of this mission is about 5 million US dollars and the work will last for two years. This will be the first inspection team to return to the Yongbyon nuclear facility since UN inspectors were expelled in 2002. Diplomats in Vienna say the team could arrive in North Korea within a week to begin monitoring the closure of the nuclear facility at Yongbyon. The IAEA meeting is currently considering some findings from a three-person team led by the deputy director...",
  "candidate_translation": "The IAEA Board of Governors has approved the closure of the Yongbyon nuclear facility."
}
